There are not many places that offer real barbacoa meat in Mexico City.  But this place is a MUST try.

We came here on the other day and The food was super delicious and big portion.  The service was exceptional. The owner was extremely welcoming and super nice.  They offer a different variety of items options on their menu.  You can order individual item or set menu .   Prices are very reasonable.

They slowly cook their barbacoa meat in a huge fire pit covered with some kind of leaves and sand.  They cooked their meat for at least few hours.

We ordered their set menu for 2 people.  It was a lot of food.  It came with consom√© ( soup ) , freshly hand made tortillas , juice,  chicharr√≥n (deep fried pork skin ) , avocado slices ,  some herbs, nopales , queso fresco ( fresh cheese ) , different types of salsas and the famous barbacoa meat.
The barbacoa meat was so tender that  melts in my mouth.  Very tasty.  Goes pretty well with their hand made tortillas .  The chicharr√≥n was perfectly made , crunchy , not oily .

Loved every bites here. Will definitely come back next time when we are in Mexico City!!!

The food here is simply incredible. We felt that it was more consistent and overall better in terms of quality, flavour and presentation than our experience at Pujol, though that was also really excellent. The one area I'd suggest improvement on would be the ambiance. There are speakers, but no music when we were there, and the lights were quite bright. Covid related - they had excellent protocols in place, which made us feel safe...but there's not a real outdoors area, so might not be something everyone is comfortable with for now. For us, it was a special occasion, and we felt it was worth it.

El men√∫ de degustaci√≥n de Quintonil es como un sue√±o hecho realidad, es un viaje de sabores, texturas y olores, bien dise√±ado, con una progresi√≥n en la que nunca se siente que un platillo desentone respecto al anterior. Tambi√©n resulta fant√°stico que todos los platillos tengan un fuerte componente de la cocina tradicional mexicana, con ingredientes y formas de preparaci√≥n tradicionales.

He probado el men√∫ con maridaje y sin √©l. La experiencia con maridaje mejora de manera sustancial. Nuevamente hubo una progresi√≥n fant√°stica, empezando con una cerveza artesanal, pasando por una gran variedad de vinos blancos y tintos (si van a tomar el maridaje no manejen despu√©s). It's rare for me to write a 2 star review but despite all our excitement our lunch at Quintonil was a big disappointment at our recent visit.

There is no doubting the talent of the chef and kitchen and overall we have no major quibbles with the quality of the food itself - though it was something in line with something we might expect in a 1 michelin star establishment rather than purportedly one of the worlds finest restaurants.  Everything looked and tasted just fine but there werent any moments of true joy or inspiration for us.

The real disappointment was in the ambience and character of the restaurant.  The lighting was beyond terrible.  The furinishings lacklustre.  The tables were placed far too close so we could hear all the conversations close to us making it difficult to really enjoy the meal or each others company.  Unbelievably, the table decor was composed of fake plastic lemons.   The cocktails we ordered were so bad they made us laugh.  The chocolates we werent ablet to finish at the end of our meal were presented to us in a shabby styroform take out box you might find a roadside cafe.

We have no qualms on spending decent money on terrific food but by the time our bill arrived we felt thoroughly cheated.

In hindsight, we wished we'd left midway through the meal.  What was meant to be one of the highlights of our trip to mexico felt more like an ordeal and we both breathed a mutual sigh of relief as we left the dark, oppressive dining room for the sunnier street outside.

The kitchen no doubt has real flair and talent, but I get a sense of a badly run business cutting corners and providing a compalcent and mediocre service to its patrons.  It is certainly no longer in any way comparable to Pujol or Central or Gaggan.

Our advice: the food is pretty fautless, but the experience overall is so charmless that we'd give it a miss till the house gets its act together.  We wish we hadnt gone.

I would NOT recommend eating here.
Our party got VIOLENTLY ILL following this meal.

I am sure this is not the case for all meals, but please have some Quality Standards.

Would it have been so hard to give her multiple pieces to use with the sauce.  When asked for a second piece of bread we got attitude.  Theservice was really terrible - we waited 10-20 minutes between finishing one course and getting the. next.  It was so bad I started timing the intervals.  At various points they came and put down plates and then removed them without serving us anything.  Our waiter would approach our table and see us sitting and waiting... a guilty look would pass over his face and then he would turn around and say nothing.  The tables around us also seemed to be waiting and bored.  If the kitchen was having issues they should have at least offered us free water or a drink or something. The bill came to $220 CAD for two of us, which would be the price for one person if we did this in Canada. We also went on Valentine's Day and they gave us an extra plate full of desserts! So good. Tourists beware - this place will try to rip you off. We started off pleasantly and enjoyed our medicore food (and good wine pours) only to be foiled by an attempted scam at the end of our meal.

The waitress who brought the bill was not one who had attended to us, and gave us a hand written tab. She then immediately told us their card reader wasn't working and we would have to pay in cash. When we looked at the "bill", we saw they had charged us more for every single item that was listed. Water bottles on the menu were listed at 25 pesos, and we had 3 but they wrote down $150 MX. Our pizzas were $110 on the menu, but they had listed them as $120. Our wine they charged $210 pesos and we couldn't dispute that unfortunately because they did not list the wine on the menu, but they did charge us for 4 instead of 3. When we told them we only had a card, they told is they could do a partial card charge and a partial cash charge which still makes zero sense to me, but by that time we were so frustrated that we just wanted to leave. We got them to agree to their posted menu prices, and our waiter claimed the upcharge was for his tip. Well, no tip for you! What a shame, this place could be great, even with the garbage food.

The restaurant setting is beautiful - there‚Äôs a Japanese zen garden vibe to it. The recurring motif of circles is prevalent both in the decor & food presentation.

Snacks: well balanced layers of flavors. The sauce for the corn is finger-licking good (please sell them in jars üòã)

Chayote: beautiful dish inside out - but relatively less memorable flavors

Ceviche: one of our favorite dishes. The mouthwatering citrus flavor will make you drink every last bit of the sauce.

Papadzul: wish there are more Korean-Mexican fusion food out there. The juiciness of the mushrooms matches phenomenally with the kimchi.

Striped bass: Japanese-influenced dish & another highlight of the meal! Everything on the plate is executed on point: from the tenderness of the sea bass, to the thoughtful sauce for the vegetables, and the sushi rice ball covered with seaweed powder. I can eat a bento box of this.

Mole: one of their signature dishes, & unfortunately the only dish we did not care for. Guess we‚Äôre just not into mole?

Palette cleanser (sorbet), yogurt ice cream, churro/fig: the palette cleanser & yogurt ice cream are too similar/repetitive IMO. Nevertheless, the yogurt ice cream is very tasty & rich in honey flavor, and reminds me of ice cream with shaved ice (common dessert in Asia). The meal wraps up perfectly with churro (hope they can make a gluten-free version in the future).

Wine pairing: excellent selection offered & reasonable pouring. I think it can be even more unique/special to feature local wines.

Seating: during COVID times, I think the seating could be further spaced out to create a better sense of social distancing.

Service: attentive & good as you would expect at a high-end establishment.

Question: are the staff saying ‚Äúadios‚Äù to the food before they were brought out from the kitchen? üòù We could not decipher what they were saying in unison.

First and foremost the food was decent but not spectacular. The first few courses were better than the rest, but I have no complaints about it. The inside of the restaurant is also beautiful and stunning.

However, the experience was horrendous because of the lack of care that the restaurant had with regards to safety. I have never been in a restaurant during COVID, in both the US and Mexico, that packs so many people in such a small area, all within touching distance from one another. While all the employees had both masks and face shields, the clients are packed almost shoulder to shoulder. I have no doubt that if one person had COVID all of us would be infected. Typically I am not too worried about the virus but Pujol was so ridiculous with this that it absolutely destroyed the experience.

I made a comment to both the waiter and the manager, and after a back and forth discussion during which they told us that they weren‚Äôt open seats because it was a full house, they finally moved us. They also gave us a few extra dishes and a quarter portion of free wine which was nice. They ended up charging us the full amount which was fine. That wasn‚Äôt the point. We didn‚Äôt sign up to pay $150+ just to complain and get an extra dish - we were there to enjoy the experience.

If the owner of the restaurant is reading this, you should feel ashamed of yourself and for putting your customers at risk. It really is unethical for such a highly regarded and expensive restaurant. Build more barriers and space out the seats. Of all restaurants in the world you can probably afford to take a slight hit for the safety of others.

If you are a potential client, I would be aware of this especially if you are in a high risk group and at the minimum ask for a seat outside or in the corner near the entrance / exit.

I thought this restaurant was very average.

We had an assortment of drinks, appetizers, and two main courses.

The drinks were two mezcal cocktails (one with kiwi, the other with pepino). The kiwi one was exceptional -- we also had a craft beer, which was great as well.

Our appetizers were very okay. We had a jicama wrap with avocado, cucumber, as well as well as a meat pastry with some dipping sauces. The jicama was refreshing but a bit bland, while the pastry was not very good at all. The flavor of the sauce was incredibly conflicting, and the pastry itself did not carry much weight.

For the main courses, we had the seared tuna and pollo with some plantains. The chicken dish was good, but a bit too sweet -- for one person to eat it was overwhelming. The tuna was well-cooked, but nothing special. It was accompanied by very stereotypical sauces.

The ambiance was quite nice, and the service was exemplary -- all of our plates were taken immediately upon completion.

I think there are certainly better options around.
